    "texts": [
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Identification features",
            "shortText": "<p>Medium-sized, densely-branched, succulent shrub with thin, segmented, green stems that branch dichotomously. Usually erect but may be spreading. Stems emit a milky latex when damaged.</p><p>Leaves reduced to tiny scales. False flowers bright yellow and appear in dense clusters at ends of stems, surrounded by five green lobes.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_1_9502",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Adult size",
            "shortText": "<p>Plants can grow to 1 m tall. Branches 30-50 mm diameter. Leaves 2-3 mm long. Flowers about 2-4 mm across.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_2_9503",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Distribution",
            "shortText": "<p><u>Global:</u> Endemic to southern Africa.</p><p><u>Local/Regional:</u> Southern Namibia to Eastern Cape.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_3_9504",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Biology",
            "shortText": "<p>Most common in coastal sands and flats but also further inland where it often grows together with the related but more robust and widespread <i>E. mauritania</i>.</p><p>Used as an ornamental in coastal and waterwise gardens.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_4_9505",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Food / prey",
            "shortText": "<p>Photosynthetic.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_5_9506",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Reproduction",
            "shortText": "<p>Flowers June to September. Pollinated by bees and flies. Seeds borne in capsules. Also grows readily from cuttings or division.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_6_9507",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Similar species",
            "shortText": "<p>The genus <i>Euphorbia</i> contains over 2000 species and is one of the most diverse of all genera of flowering plants. Numerous species occur in the region, but these differ greatly in growth form varying from trees to small species that lie close to the ground. Many are also spiny. This spineless shrublike species is most easily confuted with the Yellow milk bush <i>E. mauritanica</i> which is common across the same range and sometimes occurs in mixed stands with <i>E. burmanii</i>. That species differs by having much longer leaves (8-15 mm long) and has a central male flower surrounded by 5-7 bisexual false larger flowers 7-15 mm in diameter.&nbsp;</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_7_9508",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        }
    ],
